<div class="container">
    <h1>Polymorphism in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>
        <strong>Polymorphism</strong> allows objects to take many forms. In C#, it is achieved through <strong>method overloading</strong> (compile-time) and <strong>method overriding</strong> (runtime).  
        Polymorphism helps make code more flexible, reusable, and easier to maintain.
    </p>

    <h2>Example 1: Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Overloading Methods</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Calculator
{
    public int Add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    public double Add(double a, double b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }
}

Calculator calc = new Calculator();
Console.WriteLine(calc.Add(2, 3));
Console.WriteLine(calc.Add(2.5, 3.5));
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        In this example, the <strong>Calculator</strong> class defines two <strong>Add</strong> methods with different parameter types: <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>.  
        This is <strong>method overloading</strong>, which allows the same method name to handle different input types.  
        When we call <code>calc.Add(2, 3)</code>, the compiler chooses the <code>int</code> version. When we call <code>calc.Add(2.5, 3.5)</code>, it chooses the <code>double</code> version.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Expected Output:</strong></p>
    <pre>
5
6
    </pre>

    <h2>Example 2: Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism)</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Overriding Methods</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Animal
{
    public virtual void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Some generic sound");
    }
}

public class Dog : Animal
{
    public override void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Bark!");
    }
}

public class Cat : Animal
{
    public override void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Meow!");
    }
}

Animal myAnimal1 = new Dog();
Animal myAnimal2 = new Cat();
myAnimal1.MakeSound();
myAnimal2.MakeSound();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        Here, the base class <strong>Animal</strong> defines a method <strong>MakeSound</strong> with the <code>virtual</code> keyword.  
        The <strong>Dog</strong> and <strong>Cat</strong> classes <strong>override</strong> this method to provide their own implementations.  
        This is <strong>runtime polymorphism</strong>: the actual method that runs depends on the object type at runtime, even if the reference type is <strong>Animal</strong>.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Expected Output:</strong></p>
    <pre>
Bark!
Meow!
    </pre>

    <h2>Key Points About Polymorphism</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Method overloading allows the same method name with different parameters. The compiler decides which method to call at compile time.</li>
        <li>Method overriding allows a derived class to provide a specific implementation of a base class method. The runtime decides which method to call based on the actual object type.</li>
        <li>Polymorphism makes your code flexible, reusable, and easier to maintain.</li>
        <li>Use <code>virtual</code> in the base class and <code>override</code> in the derived class for runtime polymorphism.</li>
        <li>You can mix multiple derived classes and call the same method on a base class reference to get different behaviors.</li>
    </ul>

